Before you go shopping, check your cupboards and fridge: there may be ingredients you could use up first.
Cook in bulk and freeze leftovers in portions once they are completely cold. #FoodCrisis #costofliving #cookingonabudget #reducewaste #DW2022
If you buy bulk packs of meat or fish, separate them into portions and freeze the ones you know you won‚Äôt use before the use-by date

Add grated veg to your mince to make it go further ‚Äì try carrot, courgette and marrow.
Switch fresh fish for canned or frozen fish.
Add pasta or rice to your soups to make them go further.

Cooking on a budget 
Use less meat and bulk up stews, soups, chilies and curries with canned peas, pulses like kidney beans, butter beans and mixed beans. You could divide your usual portion of meat into two meals and add extra veg to make it go much further

You can use grated cheese straight from the freezer and it keeps for up to 4 months
Freeze chopped onion in plastic bags, then use it in any meals and bonus they are quick when you don‚Äôt have time to chop. #costofliving #dw2022 #dietitians #foodcrisis #sustainability #foodwaste

Wrap meat in individual portions in cling film or plastic bags, so you can remove them and cook them one at a time.
Bread and baked products freeze brilliantly. You can toast slices of bread from frozen; slice bagels and bread rolls before you freeze them

Thaw food overnight in the fridge, not at room temperature.
Never refreeze food if it‚Äôs already been frozen and thawed
Reheat food once only until it‚Äôs steaming hot (75ÀöC for at least two minutes).

Batch cooking 
Make sure food is cold before you freeze it, (warm food will raise the temperature of your freezer)
Label food with its name & the date 
A full freezer is more economical. If there is a lot of space, fill it with everyday items like bread & milk

Our urine should be pale straw colour or clear. If it is dark yellow or orange we need to drink more. If our urine is dark orange or brown, we are severely dehydrated and drinking plenty of fluid is essential to restore our dehydration. #NHWeek2022
Children and older adults often don‚Äôt feel thirst so checking urine colour can be an easy way for everyone to find out if their water needs are being met or not.

It is important for you to listen to your body. If you feel thirsty it is important to have a drink, as this is your body's way of telling you that you need fluid. Taking note of the colour of your urine is also a good way to check how hydrated you are.

If you are dehydrated for a long time it can start affecting your kidney function, which will then affect your body's ability to remove waste products. This can cause you to experience problems like kidney stones, urinary tract infections, and chronic renal disease.
Keeping hydrated by drinking enough is vital for good health. If you become dehydrated it can start to cause a lack of concentration, headaches, tiredness, dizziness, lightheadedness & confusion.

Common signs of malnutrition are:
unplanned weight loss ‚Äì which can cause clothes, dentures, belts or jewellery to become loose
tiredness and lethargy
alterations in mood
loss of appetite
disinterest in food and/or fluids
loss of muscle strength¬†@NHWeek

Consequences of malnutrition include:
increased risk of illness and infection
slower wound healing
increased risk of falls
low mood
reduced energy levels
reduced muscle strength
reduced quality of life
reduced independence and ability to carry out daily activities¬†@NHWeek
93 per cent are living in their own home, five per cent are living in care homes and just two per cent¬†are in hospital.@NHWeek

Malnutrition is a major public health issue costing the NHS over ¬£19 billion per year in England alone. There are approximately three million people in the UK who are malnourished or at risk of malnutrition @NHWeek

Malnutrition can often be very difficult to recognise, particularly in patients who are overweight or obese to start with. Malnutrition can happen very gradually, which can make it very difficult to spot in the early stages

Malnutrition is a state of nutrition in which a deficiency or excess (or imbalance) of energy, protein and other nutrients causes measurable adverse effects on tissue / body form (body shape, size and composition) and function and clinical outcome.
